1 Read and Combine Data

Customer <-read.csv("Customer.csv")
Sales <- read.csv(file = "Sales.csv")
df <- merge(Customer, Sales, by="CUSTOMER_NUMBER_BLINDED")

2 Data Features

data_list <- list(Customer, Sales)

# create a new column with the total sum of invoice prices per customer
df$TOTAL_PROFIT <- ave(df$GROSS_PROFIT_DEAD_NET, df$CUSTOMER_NUMBER_BLINDED, FUN = sum)

#Profitable logic
df$PROFITABLE <- ifelse(df$TOTAL_PROFIT > 0, 1, 0)

# create a new column with the total sum of invoice prices per customer
df$TOTAL_INVOICES <- ave(df$INVOICE_PRICE, df$CUSTOMER_NUMBER_BLINDED, FUN = sum)

3 Business Problem

Swire Coca-Cola wants to predict the profitability and success of new local B2B restaurants and the profitability and risk factor of current customers(quick service, restaurants, retails and etc) to make informed decisions on pricing and funding. Our team will use historical data and machine learning techniques to build a predictive model that identifies profitable restaurant types and how long it takes for both new and old customers to become profitable. The project will provide Swire Coca-Cola with insight on their current market, demands for each product and different customer segments.Our team also hope to provide Swire Coca-Cola with findings regarding customer profitability and what factors contribute towards a customer’s success and which reasons create risk for Swire.

4 Analytic objective

To create a predictive model that would highlight key indicators of success for Swire’s customers(b2b businesses and etc). This would help Swire identify and target potentially successful businesses and create a long lasting partnership. We that this would also identify key aspects of a risky businesses. We also want to deliver a model that would predict profitability based on discounts given. By doing so we hope to show that certain levels of discounts towards customers(both successful and risky ventures) play a part in the business’s profitability in the long run.Our team will test out a variety of target variables to see which target variable has better predictability when it comes to a customer’s profitability.

I will create a new column called Profitable. It will be a binary variable of 1,0 or Profitable, not profitable and I will use several predicting variables to determine the customer’s probability of being a profitable business venture for Swire.

As the semester goes on, Our team will conduct several different analysis along side the predicted model that was stated above. As we continue with the project, we hope gain a deeper understanding of the factors that affect Swire Coca-Cola’s business in order to deliver a more accurate analysis at the end of the semester.

5 Questions

Customer Segments -Where do we have the most success? -Where do we have the most customers? -Which customer category do we serve more? which customer category do we serve the least? -Which type of customers should be focused on? -When do we consider a customer inactive? or lost? -What is the distribution of the Profitable column? How many businesses are profitable and how many are not? -What are the characteristics of the businesses that Swire has partnered with in the past? Are there any common traits or patterns that successful businesses tend to exhibit?

Products -Which cold drink channel should we target the most? -Which Items are most in demand? -Is the demand for low calorie drinks increasing?

Discounts -Whats the average discount per order? -How can we distinguish if a discount has had an effect on a customer’s success? -What is our point of diminishing returns when it comes to discounts?

# Filter the data to the top 20 most profitable cities
top_cities <- df %>% 
  group_by(ADDRESS_CITY) %>% 
  summarize(TOTAL_PROFIT = sum(GROSS_PROFIT_DEAD_NET)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(TOTAL_PROFIT)) %>% 
  top_n(20, TOTAL_PROFIT) %>% 
  pull(ADDRESS_CITY)

df_filtered <- df %>% 
  filter(ADDRESS_CITY %in% top_cities)

# Create a histogram of the profitable sales by city

# Chi squared test between profitable and channels I wanted to test whether there is a significant association between two categorial variables.Based on the results, I will conclude that there is a significant association betwwen PROFITABLE and the channels.

# create a contingency table of profitable and customer trade channel
contingency_table <- df %>%
  select(PROFITABLE, CUSTOMER_TRADE_CHANNEL_DESCRIPTION) %>%
  group_by(PROFITABLE, CUSTOMER_TRADE_CHANNEL_DESCRIPTION) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = PROFITABLE, values_from = count, values_fill = 0)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'PROFITABLE'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# conduct the chi-squared test
chi_squared_test <- chisq.test(contingency_table[,2:3])

# print the results of the chi-squared test
chi_squared_test
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  contingency_table[, 2:3]
## X-squared = 39474, df = 24, p-value < 2.2e-16

16 Finding out the relationship between Physical Volume and Discounts.

How can I find the point of diminishing returns?

In this plot we can see the relationship between discounts and physical volume of orders. Higher orders mean higher discounts. Though most of Swire’s customers do not need a huge amount of discount because they do not have the capacity to sell huge amounts of product.

# Run a simple linear regression to model the relationship between discounts and physical volume
reg_model <- lm(Sales$DISCOUNT ~ Sales$PHYSICAL_VOLUME, data = Sales)

# Summarize the regression results
summary(reg_model)

17 Findings

I am very interested in finding out what is the point of diminishing returns for Swire Coca-Cola’s customers. I am interested whether smaller businesses have a faster point of diminishing returns as compared to bigger companies and whether bigger businesses tend to become profitable faster than smaller businesses.
